WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:07.293
Every reward-based update depends on whether its evaluator measures the right thing. This is the verifier problem.

2
00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:18.658
RLVR means Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards. For our repair, the verifier applies the patch, runs the cancellation tests, and returns a reproducible outcome.

3
00:00:19.525 --> 00:00:24.573
The same idea applies to checked math answers, tool states, and agent environments.

4
00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:31.983
A preference such as “patch A is cleaner” depends on a judge. A verifiable reward applies an explicit rule.

5
00:00:32.850 --> 00:00:40.758
Verifiable does not mean infallible; it means the same patch should receive the same result under the same evaluator state.

6
00:00:41.625 --> 00:00:53.077
Write the rule as r equals V of x, y, and e. X is the public task. Y is the sampled attempt. E is evaluator-only state such as hidden tests.

7
00:00:53.944 --> 00:00:58.128
For a binary verifier, reward is zero or one.

8
00:00:58.995 --> 00:01:11.773
This equation separates the setting from the optimizer. RLVR supplies reward. PPO, GRPO, or another policy optimizer supplies the update. DeepSeek-R1 is an important example of reasoning training built from this combination.

9
00:01:12.639 --> 00:01:23.911
The full loop is prompt, policy attempt, execution, verification, reward, and policy update. Automatic checks scale because a person does not need to score every trajectory.

10
00:01:24.777 --> 00:01:29.554
The verifier also becomes both the task specification and an attack surface.

11
00:01:30.421 --> 00:01:43.741
RLVR applies beyond short math answers. Code can compile and run tests. Tool agents can be checked against a target database state. Search can verify retrieved evidence. Scientific tasks can use simulators and constraints.

12
00:01:44.607 --> 00:01:51.743
It is a poor fit when quality is inherently subjective, outcomes cannot be reproduced, or the checker is easy to game.

13
00:01:52.610 --> 00:02:04.202
Verifier errors have two directions. A false negative rejects a valid solution. A false positive is more dangerous under optimization because a wrong solution receives positive gradient and can become an exploit.

14
00:02:05.069 --> 00:02:14.434
Suppose visible tests cover only three examples. Hard-coding those outputs and implementing the general rule both receive reward one. The optimizer cannot distinguish them.

15
00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:22.757
Hidden tests, randomized cases, invariants, and shadow verifiers make the measured objective closer to the intended task.

16
00:02:23.624 --> 00:02:37.626
That requires an information boundary. The policy sees the public task and allowed observations. The evaluator alone sees hidden checks and anti-cheat state. Training-only teacher evidence belongs in a third protected channel.

17
00:02:38.492 --> 00:02:47.134
So “RLVR with GRPO” is precise: the first term names how outcomes are labeled, and the second names how those labels become an update.
